===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|grinden}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|grindan}}, (cognate with Dutch {{m|nl|grind||gravel, shingle}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*grindaną}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*ghrendh-||crushing}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈɡɹaɪnd/|lang=en}}, {{audio|en-us-grind.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|aɪnd|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|grinds|grinding|ground|past2=grinded}} (''see usage notes below'')

# To reduce to [[smaller]] pieces by [[crush]]ing with [[lateral]] motion.
# To [[shape]] with the force of [[friction]].
#: '''''grind''' a lens''
#: '''''grind''' an axe''
# {{context|metalworking|lang=en}} To [[remove]] material by [[rub]]bing with an [[abrasive]] surface.
# To become ground, pulverized, or polished by friction.
#: ''This corn '''grinds''' well.''
#: ''Steel '''grinds''' to a sharp edge.''
# To move with much difficulty or friction; to [[grate]].
# {{context|sports|lang=en}} To [[slide]] the flat portion of a [[skateboard]] or [[snowboard]] across an obstacle such as a railing.
# To [[oppress]], [[hold down]] or [[weaken]].
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} To [[rotate]] the [[hips]] [[erotic]]ally.
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} To [[dance]] in a [[sexual]]ly suggestive way with both partners in very close proximity, often pressed against each other.
# {{context|video games|lang=en}} To repeat a task in order to gain [[level up|levels]] or items.
# To produce [[mechanical]]ly and [[repetitive]]ly as if by turning a [[crank]].
# To instill through repetitive teaching.
#: '''''Grinding''' lessons into students' heads does not motivate them to learn.''
# {{context|slang|Hawaii|lang=en}} To [[eat]].
#: ''Eh, brah, let's go '''grind'''.''
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} To work or study hard; to [[hustle]] or [[drudge]].
#: {{rfquotek|Farrar}}

====Usage notes====
* In the sports and video game senses, the past participle and past tense form {{term|grinded|lang=en}} is often used instead of the irregular form {{term|ground|lang=en}}.
* Historically, there also existed a past participle form {{term|grounden|lang=en}}, but it is now archaic or obsolete.
* When used to denote sexually suggestive dancing between two partners, the past participle and past tense form {{term|grinded|lang=en}} is almost always used.

